#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:1
msgid "How Guidelines Are Written"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:3
msgid ""
"The guidelines in this collection reflect widely-recognized **philosophy** "
"for writing high-quality software. Three books have influenced the "
"guidelines the most:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:7
msgid ""
"[_The Art of Readable Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/the-art-"
"of/9781449318482/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:8
msgid ""
"[_Clean Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/clean-code-"
"a/9780136083238/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:9
msgid "[_Code Complete_](https://stevemcconnell.com/books/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:11
msgid ""
"The guidelines are derived from **code review experience**, where we point "
"out code smells, observe anti-patterns, and fix recurring bugs. By the time "
"the initial version of these guidelines was formulated, Asterinas had seen "
"thousands of code reviews. We collected the historical review comments as a "
"[dataset](https://github.com/asterinas/pr-review-analysis) and used it as "
"both inspiration and evidence."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:19
msgid ""
"The remainder of this page has two parts. The [Philosophy](#philosophy) "
"section captures foundational beliefs about what makes code understandable "
"and maintainable. The [Quality Criteria](#quality-criteria) section defines "
"how individual guidelines are written and accepted into this collection."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:26
msgid "Philosophy"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:28
msgid "Minimize time to understand"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:30
msgid ""
"Code should be written to minimize the time it would take someone else to "
"fully understand it. This is the fundamental theorem of readability and the "
"single most important measure of code quality in this project. \"Someone "
"else\" includes your future self."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:37
msgid ""
"Code is read far more often than it is written. If a technique makes code "
"shorter but harder to follow at a glance, choose clarity over brevity."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:42
msgid "Managing complexity is the primary technical imperative"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:44
msgid ""
"No one can hold an entire modern program in their head. The purpose of every "
"technique in software construction — decomposition, naming, encapsulation, "
"abstraction — is to break complex problems into simple pieces so that you "
"can safely focus on one thing at a time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:50
msgid "Craftsmanship and care"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:52
msgid ""
"Clean code looks like it was written by someone who cares. Professionalism "
"means never knowingly leaving a mess. The only way to go fast is to keep the "
"code clean at all times."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:56
msgid "Continuous improvement"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:58
msgid ""
"Leave code cleaner than you found it. Small, steady improvements — renaming "
"a variable, extracting a function, eliminating duplication — prevent code "
"from rotting over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:64
msgid "Quality Criteria"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:66
msgid ""
"Every guideline carries a **descriptive short name** in kebab-case (e.g., "
"`explain-variables`, `lock-ordering`). Short names are kept **intact** even "
"as the guidelines evolve and should be used when referencing guidelines in "
"code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:71
msgid ""
"A guideline is accepted into this collection when it satisfies all four "
"quality criteria:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:74
msgid ""
"**Concrete** — Framed as an actionable item with an illustrating example "
"when possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:76
msgid "**Concise** — Kept short; we do not want to intimidate readers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:78
msgid ""
"**Grounded** — Opinionated or non-obvious guidelines should include a \"See "
"also\" line with supportive materials (literature, PR reviews, codebase "
"examples)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:81
msgid ""
"**Relevant** — Included only if it has codebase examples, prevents a past "
"bug, or matches anti-patterns observed in code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:86
msgid ""
"When present, the **\"See also\" line** lists sources in the order: "
"literature; PR reviews; codebase examples. Not every guideline needs all "
"three; for strongly opinionated or non-obvious guidelines, include the line "
"by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:92
msgid ""
"Do not add a guideline whose only value is mechanical enforcement already "
"provided by automated tools such as [rustfmt](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rustfmt) and [clippy](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy). If a tool-"
"enforced convention appears frequently in review or needs project-specific "
"rationale, keep a short explanatory guideline and point to the tool "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:99
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:101
msgid "Below is a sample guideline demonstrating these conventions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:127
msgid "This example demonstrates:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:128
msgid ""
"A stable short name (`explain-variables`) shown parenthetically and used as "
"the heading anchor"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:129
msgid "A one-sentence actionable recommendation followed by a code example"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:130
msgid ""
"A \"See also\" line ordered as: literature, PR reviews, codebase examples"
msgstr ""
